ght. &#10;Religious exemption is one of several ways families can legally homeschool in Virginia. It is also one of the least-utilized. A tiny percentage of legal homeschoolers use this option, which requires a lengthy and onerous application process, and which requires all homeschooled students 14 and older to write their OWN declaration of homeschooling for the sake of religious freedom--a detail merely alluded to in this biased article. &#10;Our religious exemption family is led by two Ivy-League educated parents, one an attorney, one who has her own business. Our children start taking college classes at the beginning of high school, and will have taken more (self-taught) AP exams by the age of 16 than 99.9% of Virginia high school grads have taken by graduation. Where is the lengthy Post article about our oldest child, and her passionate beliefs about the benefits of freedom? Why not paint all religious exemption homeschoolers with our brush? &#10;Because it would not fit with the Post's agenda, of government control and interference with the sanctity of the family. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1382" language="en" documentId="343" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="homeschool4joy" date="7/29/2013 2:20 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375100402-448-896" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="343" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="312"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="313" end="747"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="748" end="1260"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="1261" end="1382"/><cas